<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><p>Discuss about different JSON data types.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is the most widely used data format for data interchange on the web.Â JSON is a lightweight text-based, data-interchange format and it is completely language-independent. It is based on a subset of the JavaScript programming language and it is easy to understand and generate.</p>
<p>JSON supports mainly 6 data types:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>string</li>
<li>number</li>
<li>boolean</li>
<li>null</li>
<li>object</li>
<li>array</li>
</ol>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>1. String:</strong></span></p>
<p>Strings in JSON must be written in double quotes.</p>
<p><code>{<span class="jsstringcolor">"name"</span>:<span class="jsstringcolor">"John"</span>}</code></p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>2. Number:</strong></span></p>
<p>Numbers in JSON must be an integer or a floating point.</p>
<p><code>{<span class="jsstringcolor">"age"</span>:<span class="jsnumbercolor">30</span>}</code></p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>3. Boolean:</strong></span></p>
<p>Values in JSON can be true/false.</p>
<p><code>{<span class="jsstringcolor">"sale"</span>:<span class="jskeywordcolor">true</span>}</code></p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>4. null:</strong></span></p>
<p>Values in JSON can be null.</p>
<p><code>{<span class="jsstringcolor">"middlename"</span>:<span class="jskeywordcolor">null</span>}</code></p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>5. Objects:</strong></span></p>
<p>Values in JSON can be objects.</p>
<p><code>{<br />
<span class="jsstringcolor">Â  Â  "employee"</span>:{<span class="jsstringcolor">"name"</span>:<span class="jsstringcolor">"John"</span>,Â <span class="jsstringcolor">"age"</span>:<span class="jsnumbercolor">30</span>,Â <span class="jsstringcolor">"city"</span>:<span class="jsstringcolor">"New York"</span>}<br />
}</code></p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>6. Array:</strong></span></p>
<p>Values in JSON can be arrays.</p>
<p><code>{<br />
<span class="jsstringcolor">Â  Â  "employees"</span>:[<span class="jsstringcolor">"John"</span>,Â <span class="jsstringcolor">"Anna"</span>,Â <span class="jsstringcolor">"Peter"</span>]<br />
}</code></p>
</div>
<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>What is DTD? Create a XML file and write its equivalent DTD.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>DTD stands for Document Type Definition. It&#8217;s a way to describe the structure and properties of an XML document. It defines the elements, attributes, and the order in which they appear in an XML document.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s an example of an XML file and its equivalent DTD:</p>
<p>XML File:</p>
<pre class="EnlighterJSRAW" data-enlighter-language="generic">&lt;?xml version="1.0"?&gt;
&lt;library&gt;
&lt;book ISBN="123456789"&gt;
&lt;title&gt;Sample Book&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;author&gt;John Doe&lt;/author&gt;
&lt;genre&gt;Fiction&lt;/genre&gt;
&lt;price&gt;19.99&lt;/price&gt;
&lt;/book&gt;
&lt;book ISBN="987654321"&gt;
&lt;title&gt;Another Book&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;author&gt;Jane Smith&lt;/author&gt;
&lt;genre&gt;Non-Fiction&lt;/genre&gt;
&lt;price&gt;24.99&lt;/price&gt;
&lt;/book&gt;
&lt;/library&gt;</pre>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Equivalent DTD:<code><br />
</code></p>
<pre class="EnlighterJSRAW" data-enlighter-language="generic">&lt;!DOCTYPE library [
    &lt;!ELEMENT library (book+)&gt;
    &lt;!ELEMENT book (title, author, genre, price)&gt;
    &lt;!ATTLIST book ISBN CDATA #REQUIRED&gt;
    &lt;!ELEMENT title (#PCDATA)&gt;
    &lt;!ELEMENT author (#PCDATA)&gt;
    &lt;!ELEMENT genre (#PCDATA)&gt;
    &lt;!ELEMENT price (#PCDATA)&gt;
]&gt;
</pre>
